remarks: A very free fuga based on an idea asserted in another comment.  This whole song, anyway, counts a lot of cadential clausules for very few CAD actually audible, due to a lot of dovetails and a 'restless'behaviour. The CAD I selected is inverted, I cannot indicate it... As the soggetto of 'Vidi speciosam'is used again on 'Cuius inastimabilis', I have selected the latter, though I do not describe it. (after reflection, I find the actual CAD on bar 28, it could be the model of the CAD in the mass. I will indicate it in another comment)

remarks: The first two entrances are strict, as usual; the third is freely diminished in rhythm and lacks its final note (or one could say the final melodic interval is flexed from a 2nd, A-G to a 3rd, A-F)
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: The altus and bassus make use of two repeated motives: (1) a rising "cumulative fourth" consisting of a rising second + rising third in minims, and (2) a stepwise falling fourth in dotted minim & crotchets. In one place in the altus the two motives are spliced together to form a countermelody beneath the first note of the soggetto; otherwise they occur separately. The motives don't line up with the subject consistently, so they don't form NIms. Could be considered "contrapunto fugato"?
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: New material in Gombert related to the descending thirds from the 2nd and 4th phrases of the Cadéac in a new combination
observer.name: Ian Lorenz

remarks: Superius/tenor in strict fuga at the lower fifth as usual. Third entrance in the altus truncated after its fourth note, after which it continues in free counterpoint. Fourth entrance dubious, if it is considered an imitative entrance at all: it comprises only the first two notes, with the interval between them flexed from a 2nd to a 3rd.
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: The chant melody has a built-in repetition at this point, and Mouton sets both repetitions identically, meaning that the complete four-voice complex formed by superius/tenor fuga + free altus and bassus is immediately repeated, without any change or exchange of voices,

remarks: The countersubject to the chant soggetto is slightly flexed after its fourth note: either B-C-G or B-G. After the second NIm presentation the countersubject is brought into fuga with itself, though these entrances are incomplete. There is a suggestion of periodicity in the regular entrances of the countersubject every four breves.
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: These are 4-voice NIMs, in which the ornamented chant melody provides one subject. The second presentation is rotated (invertible counterpoint): countersubject three, which was in the bassus in the first presentation, is now moved up an octave into the contratenor. There is a brief suggestion of fuga on countersubject 2 in the first three notes of the quinta vox in b. 14.

The discantus also participates in the first and third presentations of this new non-imitative block (not indicated in the data entry for clarity)
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: This is really an MTI presentation. Josquin brings in fuga entrances of the chant-derived descending-fourth motive alternately at 2-sb and 1-sb time intervals. As a result, the lattice of entrances involves *two* different repeated imitative duos, both altered  through ic12. Entrances separated by 2sb are at 8+ and 5-; entrances separated by 1sb are at 4- and 9+.
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: Direct (quasi-ostinato) repetition of a cadential module in the same two voices.

remarks: The upper four voices form a lattice of invertible periodic entrances, with a repeating pattern of relationships creating two repetitions corresponding to the motivic repetition within the chant melody. The lower two voices form two NIms with the subject, only one of which is notated here.
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: This is the second of two NIms formed by the chant subject (in periodic entrances in the upper four voices) and a countersubject in one of the two lowest voices. (See the other relationship for a description of the PEn and the first NIm).

remarks:
Here Josquin breaks the chant phrase into two motives, one corresponding to "et mittens" and the other to "sic salutavit". The "et mittens" motive forms a non-imitative duo which is repeated almost immediately by the same voices at the same pitch; the countersubject of this non-imitative duo is shared with the *other* non-imitative cell, as indicated here by the "fuga" entry. See the other relationship for details of the second non-imitative cell.

remarks: The chant is used as the subject of a complex passage involving both fuga and non-imitative duos (recorded in separate relationships). The most extensive entrances are in the tenor and cantus; the other voices take only a three-note head-motive from the chant melody. The combination of the long tenor entrance with the three-note head-motive in the sexta pars forms a miniature imitative duo which is repeated by the cantus and bassus. More significant modular repetition arises from the presence of countersubjects (analysed separately)
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: This is the simpler of the two non-imitative modules in which the chant soggetto participates in this passage

remarks: This is a *3-voice* NIm with two presentations. The top voice has a three-note head-motive derived from the chant; the middle voice is an independent motive consisting of a rising fourth followed by a cantizans cadence; the bottom voice begins with the same three-note head-motive (rhythmicised differently) followed by a motive which engages in voice-exchange with the middle voice. In the first presentation of the module, the first three notes of the rising-fourth motive complete a statement of the chant soggetto (see the relationship recording details of the fuga in this passage). In the second NIm presentation this motive occurs independently, without the preceding chant segment.
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: As in the previous section there are two substantial entrances of a chant-derived soggetto, and two fragmentary entrances of its three-note head-motive (both in the altus). The latter do not participate in any modular repetition (see other relationship for details of the NIm in this section) and are probably opportunistic entrances, perhaps (hypothetically) the last to be "fitted in" to an existing structure in the compositional process?
observer.name: Jon Oddie

For the purposes of this relationship only the portion of the chant soggetto that participates in the NIm is shown, although in both cases it is part of a longer fuga entrances. Motive 1 (A-G-F) comes from the chant at "-gris medi-"; motive 2 (G-F-E-C-D) is always heard in one of the bass voices, followed by tenorizans or basizans motion; motive 3 (A-B-C-A) is usually heard in an inner voice; motive 4 is a decorated cantizans cadence. We hear two different three-voice combinations of these four motives in alteration: first 1+2+3, then 2+3+4, then repeat. In other words, motives 2+3 are heard each time, in combination either with the soggetto (motive 1) or with the cantizans cadence (motive 4)
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: Pieton has concealed the underlying periodicity of this fuga: if we judge from the *second* note of the chant soggetto, this is a PEn(sta) with entrances at the semibreve at the upper fourth. However, the variable length of the subject's first note conceals this regularity, to the extent that the tenor entrance on G which begins first is actually the *comes* to the *dux* represented by the sexta pars entrance on D. The third entrance in the quinta pars is fragmentary.
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: The material Willaert borrowed from b. 55 is part of a NIm in Josquin, not noted here because the other subject is not borrowed.
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: Every movement of the Willaert piece is structured as a double canon for [discantus], [contratenor primus], tenor and bassus (in some order).  Since the time and pitch interval between the first and second pairs of voices is always the same, every section consists of overlapping ID presentations. Only the portion of the ID which also participates in the NIm is selected here.
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: This duo begins imitatively with entrances of a 3-note head motive, followed by differing continuations; the continuation of the upper/leading entrance in Josquin's duos is not borrowed and is not indicated here.
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: The IDs arise as a consequence of the double-canon structure; only the portion involving borrowed material is highlighted here. The borrowed soggetto divides into two motives (A-Bb-A and A-G-A-Bb-A), which Willaert brings back at the conclusion of the canonic phrase in the upper voices. Their overlapping with the repetition of the opening duo in the lower voices results in additional fuga and NIms where the four voices overlap in bb. 40--48
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: This is one voice of a NIm in Josquin's motet; the other subject is not selected as it is not borrowed here (it was used on its own as a countersubject in Willaert's first point of imitation).
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: This segment of the double canon is heard only once (it is not repeated by the lower voices) due to its proximity to the final cadence of the section.
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: Within the context of the double-canon, Willaert contrives to quote Josquin's NIm in two different ways.  The initial canonic entrances of the borrowed subject (tenor/bassus) are accompanied by the borrowed countersubject in the free voices (contratenor secundus/vagans). The second set of canonic entrances (discantus/contratenor primus) overlap with the tail of the canon in the lower voices, and Willaert concludes the canonic phrase with the countersubject so that the overlap of the voice pairs produces two more presentations of the NIm (inverted and transposed). The end of the canonic phrase in the upper voices accordingly produces two final entrances of the countersubject without the accompanying subject.

remarks: This borrowing is described in Bernadette Nelson's 2002 article: see ex. 4, p. 371. Morales has taken a complete four-voice complex from Mouton, consisting of two voices in fuga together with their accompanying "free" voices. Morales'repetition of the borrowed material produces a quasi-NIm, though neither figure taken from the free voices is repeated exactly in its entirety. Only the conclusion of the borrowed material in the bassus is repeated (C-D-E-D in b. 9-10 becomes F-G-G-A-G in b. 12-13, with the addition of an octave leap). Meanwhile, only the skeleton of the borrowed motive in the tenor of b. 9-10 is repeated in the altus of b. 12-13, omitting the cantizans cadence; however, because the added head motive in b. 8-9/11-12 is also repeated, the entrance maintains its identity as a countersubject to the main chant soggetto.

mt_fp_comment: These two segments based on similar materials are separated by another segment based on borrowed material from Josquin's setting of the analogous chant segment (but without his chant soggetto). This gives this section an overall ABA form in which A contains only borrowed chant material and B contains only borrowed polyphonic material.
remarks: The chant melody is heard in cantus-firmus fashion three times: first incomplete in the tenor; then complete and ornamented in the cantus; finally complete and unornamented in the tenor. These statements are combined with entrances of a "countersubject" in the other voices, but it does not line up to form modules; instead, it combines with the cantus firmus in varying ways in "contrapunto fugato" fashion. (The first three entrances of the countersubject are periodic, but without enough overlap to produce modular repetition).

remarks: This passage basically consists of four presentations of an imitative duo, plus one extra entrance (tenor, bb. 67-69). The first two presentations of the duo also include a non-imitative tail in the lower voice. The third presentation of the duo is inverted (ic12) and flexed. Not recorded in the data are two entrances of a secondary motive in the upper voices of bb. 64-66: this motive resembles the tail of the main subject in diminished rhythmic values, and it is also identical to the motive treated in fuga in bb. 22-28 of this movement (and analogous places in other mvts.)

remarks: Morales sets the final phrase of the text, 'Quoniam tu solus sanctus', in what is arguably the most extended & complex passage of fuga in the piece so far. Some of the fragmentary semi-imitative entrances of the subject (those which do not begin on its first note) are selected in the score, but not included in the analysis of fuga given here. The altus shadows the bassus in bb. 105-7 and 109-10. Not notated in this relationship but also contributing to the complexity of the passage is the presence of a cantus firmus drawn from a different chant segment in the cantus of bb. 97-102.

remarks: This is a massive MTI presentation with repeating modules at S1, S2 and S3 time intervals. Its full form would require further analysis, but two features stand out immediately: (1) there is an element of heightening tension in the way that Morales draws the final four entrances into closer stretto ; (2) there is a subtle element of formal return or 'framing'in the fact that a stretto interlock at the S1 time interval is used only at the beginning and at the end.

musical_type: Fuga, Periodic entry, Imitative duo, Non-imitative duo, Interval patterns
remarks: There are two presentations of a 3-voice NIm consisting of chant soggetto and two imitative entrances of the borrowed motive. The leading, lower imitative entrance is amplified through sequential splicing: the motive is heard twice, with the last note of the first instance also being the first note of the second instance. The shorter following entrance then runs in parallel thirds with the leading entrance.

remarks: This passage consists of two presentations of a three-voice complex consisting of two voices in flexed fuga with a countersubject. There is a lot of flexing and re-splicing going on in the second presentation of this three-voice complex, so the beginnings and endings are the same, but the middle is different, and the voice roles are reshuffled.
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: The form of this fuga can be thought of as ABA. Each A consists of three entrances in the lower three voices (altus/bassus/tenor), with the first two in close fuga and the third a near-singleton (M1/6; 5-5+ in the first A, 5-1+ in the second). The B is the cantus entrance in bb. 74--75. Also, the pattern of which entrances are the original form and which the alternative "flexed" form is interesting: if X is the original and Y the form that first appears in the cantus singleton entrance, the pattern is XXXY(Y')YX, with (Y') representing a form with additional flexing at its last interval. In short, there are ABA forms on two different levels. (Is there possible symbolism somehow relating this to "crucifixus"?)
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: The presentation type is close to two contrapuntal duos than to homorhythm, but the relationship to the model suggests that all four voices are part of the same event.

remarks: The last two fuga entrances are tricky: because the first note of the bassus entrance is lengthened from a minim to a dotted semibreve, the bassus enters one minim earlier than the altus; nevertheless, from the second note of the subject onwards the altus functions as the guide and the bassus as the consequent, following the altus one minim *later* and repeating the imitative duo of the first two entrances in the passage. The data above reflect this "normalized" view of the contrapuntal relationship rather than the literal relationships between each entrance's first note.

remarks: In Josquin, the cantizans cadence in the upper voice of the second NIm presentation is embedded in a longer repeated subject; only the portion which has an analogue in Willaert's Kyrie has been selected here
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: These IDs arise as a consequence of the canonic structure (each voice of the canon begins with the imitative subject which Josquin had treated in a PEn).
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: These entrances are part of a NIm in Josquin (other voice not shown since it is not quoted)
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: The NIm formed by the borrowed subject with a new CS is presented twice in complete form, and a final time in fragmentary form (retaining only the last 3 notes of the CS). The third "presentation" is barely there at all: it shares only two notes of the CS with the others. It is included in this analysis only because of the interesting cadential contrast: the other 3 presentations imply but evade a cadence, whereas in this one the cantizans cadence figure is completed.
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: These entrances form NIMs in Josquin, whose other voices are not shown since they are not borrowed

remarks: The first two presentations of the borrowed NIm are formed by one of its two subjects in the canonic voices, with the other subject introduced in the free voices. The latter two presentations occur where the end of one canonic duo in the tenor and bassus overlaps with the start of the next canonic duo in the discantus and contratenor: here, Willaert has ended the canonic subject with one of the NIm subjects, so that the overlap of the two canonic duos produces two more NIm presentations. (This is a technique Willaert uses elsewhere in the mass).
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: These head-motives are followed by longer continuations which, in canon, form an extended ID; they are analysed simply as fuga here since there is no substantial overlap between each entrance of the common head motive.
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: Same remark applies as in the Gloria: these head-motives initiate a large-scale canonic ID, but they are analysed as fuga here since there is no substantial overlap between the common head-motives
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: The first pair of entrances form a NIm, whose other subject is not borrowed. Time interval of imitation changes to B3 in the second pair of entrances.
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: The soggetto indicated in the bass is not imitated in Josquin, but its contour is borrowed by Willaert for his imitative subject.
observer.name: Jon Oddie

remarks: Willaert increases the contrapuntal density by giving the contratenor secundus two "semi-imitative" (SIm) partial entrances, beginning at the fourth note of the subject.
observer.name: Jon Oddie
